40|$|The {{politics}} of town meetings proposes that town <b>hall</b> <b>meetings</b> are institutions of representative democracy that present {{an opportunity for}} constituents to hold their elected representatives accountable in a public setting. Constituent relations-in-interaction glosses {{a complex set of}} interactional practices and procedures through which ensembles of participants bring town <b>hall</b> <b>meetings,</b> as structures of social interaction, into being. This study uses conversation analysis, the study of talk-in-interaction, to show that the {{politics of}} town <b>hall</b> <b>meetings</b> orients to three types of accountability: Interactional accountability, political accountability, and public accountability. The articulation of these accountability types provides a sense of overall-structural organization to the structure and activities giving shape to town <b>hall</b> <b>meetings.</b> ...|$|R
